{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5f7c568d-a19f-4afd-bb88-2a99a6b87a1f","content":"In .NET MAUI, `Application.OnStart/OnSleep/OnResume` still exist but the recommended approach is **Window lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Key mappings:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window Event |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Window.Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Window.Stopped` / `Window.Backgrounding` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Window.Resumed` |\n\nUse `Backgrounding` instead of `Stopped` if you need to save state, as it provides a `BackgroundingEventArgs` with a `State` property for persisting data.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d3c7b86a-97bf-4348-aca5-d3419eff07a9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class. Specifically:\n\n- `OnStart` → `Window.Created` event or override `Window.OnCreated()`\n- `OnSleep` → `Window.Backgrounding` event or override `Window.OnBackgrounding()`\n\n\n- `OnResume` → `Window.Resumed` event or override `Window.OnResumed()`\n\nYou can also use the `ILifecycleEvents` interface for platform-specific lifecycle events.\n\nActually, I should clarify — the `Application` class in .NET MAUI still has `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` methods, so they weren't removed, but they're considered legacy. The recommended approach is to use `Window` lifecycle events instead, like `Window.Created`, `Window.Activated`, `Window.Deactivated`, and `Window.Backgrounding`.\n\nThe direct mappings are `OnStart` → `Window.Created`, `OnSleep` → `Window.Stopped` or `Window.Backgrounding`, and `OnResume` → `Window.Resumed`. I can hook into these by overriding `CreateWindow()` and returning a custom `Window` subclass.","outputTokens":831,"requestId":"9BC1:1B1DA8:5C0938B:674EB3E:69EC0EF4"},"id":"9d9e793a-3163-4bf6-b815-e469b5029ffb","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:46:58.526Z","parentId":"9a68d065-cd8d-47b0-9e02-37881b3884f3"}
